gs of mountains that encircle its central depression, creating a visually stunning and intricate landscape. The basin\'s floor also exhibits a variety of geological features, including smooth plains and fractures, offering insights into Mercury\'s complex geological history. Caloris Basin\'s study has been instrumental in understanding the processes of planetary formation and impact cratering in the early solar system, making it a significant focus of planetary research and exploration.','Caloris Basin',11,1,12,2,'Sightseeing the majestic storms, marveling at the mesmerizing cloud formations, capturing breathtaking photos of the turbulent atmosphere, experiencing the thrill of witnessing atmospheric drama, and feeling the awe of standing in the midst of cosmic spectacle.','Sky diving, Para Gliding','Whirlwind, turbulent, tempestuous, tumultuous, chaotic, unpredictable, fierce, cyclonic, raging, tumultuous, turbulent, atmospheric mayhem.','Great aurora, solar eclipse'),(6,2,3.8,312000000,'Mercury, the innermost planet in our solar system, features extensive geological features known as scarps and rupes. Scarps are long cliffs or escarpments, while rupes are fault-line cliffs. These features are a result of the planet\'s shrinking and cooling over billions of years. The scarps and rupes on Mercury can stretch for hundreds of kilometers and rise as high as a kilometer. They provide valuable geological insights into the planet\'s history and its dynamic evolution. These geological features are evidence of Mercury\'s contraction, where the planet\'s interior cooled, causing its crust to wrinkle and buckle, creating the prominent scarps and rupes we observe today. Studying these formations helps scientists understand the processes that have shaped Mercury\'s surface over geological time scales.','Scrapes and Rupes',12,1,13,1,'Sightseeing the majestic storms, marveling at the mesmerizing cloud formations, capturing breathtaking photos of the turbulent atmosphere, experienc